############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context('Numeric'); $gt = GraphTool("{line, solid, (1, 4), (6, 6)}")->with( bBox => [-7, 7, 7, -7], showInStatic => 0, );
$image_1 = createLaTeXImage(); $image_1->addToPreamble(latexImagePreamble()); $image_1->BEGIN_LATEX_IMAGE \begin{tikzpicture} \begin{axis}[ width=0.47\orccaprintwidth, ] \addplot+[guideline] coordinates {(1,4) (6,4) (6,6)}; \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1,4)}; \addplot {2/5*(x-1)+4}; \end{axis} \end{tikzpicture}
END_LATEX_IMAGE
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Plot the line with equation [`y=\frac{2}{5}(x-1)+4\text{.}`]
[_]{$gt}{1}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION We can "see" from the equation that [`(1,4)`] is a point on the line. The first step in making a plot is to go to that point on the graph. We also see the slope is [`\frac{2}{5}\text{,}`] so from our launch point of [`(1,4)\text{,}`] we can move forward [`5`] and up [`2`] to find a second point on the line.
>> [@image(insertGraph($image_1), width=>282)@]* <<
END_PGML_SOLUTION
